" alt="My Image" style="width: 200px;"> Have you ever wondered what if things had turned out differently? What if a single choice. one word, one action had changed the fate of a character in a book? The story you know isn’t the only one. Time has a way of twisting, and showing paths not taken. And now you can step onto those roads yourself. Slip into the shoes of your favourite characters from Cornwall: Lisa, Callum, Lewis, Elliot, Tomo, and Jessica. Relive the key moments where everything could have gone another way. See the world through their eyes as it unravels. Decide who survives… and who doesn’t. Every choice branches into a new story. Every what if whispers a different ending. Nothing is ever set in stone. The question is what will you change? <h1>[[PLAY|starting]]</h1><h1>Choose your Character</h1> The world has already ended but the story hasn’t. Each life holds a different thread, a different // What if // Step into their shoes, make their choices, and see how fate twists when you pull at it. Who will you become? * [[Callum]] — A battle-scarred ex-soldier turned coder. Haunted by the past, forced into the role of reluctant mentor. *What if he failed… or refused to lead at all?* * [[Tomo]] — Big-hearted, loyal, bruised by loss. *What if grief drove him reckless or turned him into the strongest of them all?* * [[Elliot]] — A teenage neighbour forced to grow up at gunpoint. *What if he froze, faltered… or became harder than anyone expected?* * [[Jessica]] — Resourceful and instinctively brave, a quiet strength others rely on. *What if she broke under pressure or rose higher than anyone imagined?* * [[Lewis]] — Sharp-tongued, restless, quick with a joke to mask the fear. *What if he ran when it mattered or finally stood his ground?* * [[Lisa]] — A sergeant with steel in her veins, bound to duty even as the world crumbles. *What if she disobeyed Your monitors flicker, then cut to black. The router clicks once and falls silent. No signal. No Wi-Fi. Your phone shows **No Service**. For a moment, the only sound is the tick of the old space heater cooling down. The barn feels suddenly very empty. What do you do? [[Stay in the barn and wait it out->StayInBarn]] [[Grab your coat and head up the lane to find signal->FindSignal]] [[Get in the car and drive to Mark’s place->DriveToMark]] The alarm blared. Elliot slammed it quiet and lay there, warm and comfortable, staring at the ceiling. Does he drag himself up… or stay in bed, already thinking up an excuse to tell Olé and the lads about why he’s not heading to Penzance? [[Get up|ElliotGetsUp]] [[Stay in bed|ElliotStayBed]] Elliot’s eyes were wide, pleading. “Please… can we look for my mum?” Lisa hesitated, torn. The risk was obvious, but so was the hope in his voice. What does she decide? [[“It’s risky… but alright. We’ll prep and go.”->SearchForMum]] [[She shakes her head. “No, lad. Too dangerous. I’m sorry.”->NoSearch]] Jessica sat stiffly in the tractor beside Tomo as they rattled away from the farm. Up ahead, a car was pulled over on the verge, doors hanging open. Dark splashes of blood stained the tarmac. Jessica gagged, shoved the door open, and stumbled out, retching by the roadside. “I… I can’t do this,” she gasped, wiping her mouth with the back of her hand. Tomo leaned out, his voice firm but steady. “You’re stronger than you think, maid. Stronger than you know.” What does Jessica do? " alt="My Image" style="width: 300px;"> The tractor judders to a halt at the rise, engine ticking as Tomo squints across the field. Figures drift through the morning mist beyond the far gate. Four maybe five. They move strangely. Not walking proper. Staggering, lurching, one of them pitching sideways into a fence post before shuffling on. Tomo mutters, “Brilliant.” He cups his hands and shouts across the field: “Oi! That’s private land!” The wind steals his words. The figures keep coming. Closer now. Clothes torn, soaked. Wrong. One turns, slow and jerky, like its head and body don’t quite belong together. Another falls face-first, then rises again—limbs bent the wrong way, like a broken puppet. Tomo grips his old ash stick tighter. His gut churns. Something isn’t right. What do you do? [[Ignore them, get back in the tractor and leave it be->tomo_ignore]] [[Call out again, then head back to the farmhouse to phone the police->tomo_callout]] [[Climb the gate and confront them directly with your stick->tomo_confront]] You decide to bunker down. Maybe the power will come back. Maybe the network will sort itself. For now, you sit in the silence of the barn, nursing cold coffee. The minutes stretch on. Outside, the lane remains quiet. Too quiet. [[Feeling tired get your head down, you woke up early->BarnWaitLonger]] [[Do some admin and wait it out->FindSignallate]]You grab your coat, pocket your phone, and head up the lane. No signal bars. Not even a flicker. At the top of the lane, you spot a lone figure by the hedgerow — Elliot. Jane’s lad. Rucksack hanging off one shoulder, pale face staring down the road. This is where your story really begins. [[Call out to Elliot->MeetElliot]]Keys in hand, you decide not to wait. Mark texted you last night — maybe he knows more. You get in the car, engine coughing to life. The road ahead is misted and empty. As you drive north, the world grows stranger. Silent houses. Empty roads. No sign of police, no traffic, just a creeping unease, You pass a sole person waiting at the side of the road he looked vaguely familar [[Keep driving->NorthboundChaos]] [[Turn back and see if he " alt="My Image" style="width: 200px;"> You slump on the sofa, convincing yourself there’s nothing to do but wait. The silence presses down until your eyes grow heavy… and you drift off. You wake with a start. A sound filters in through the barn walls a low, drawn-out moaning. Currious, you step outside. Near the edge of your lane, a group staggers through the mist. Clothes torn, faces smeared with blood. One of them looks familiar, Jane’s lad. Elliot. “You lot alright?” you call, moving closer. No answer. Just vacant eyes and twitching hands. You take another step. That’s when they surge forward. Too fast. Too many. Hands claw. Teeth sink. Pain flares white-hot. You scream, but it dies in your throat. Darkness takes you. You wake again moments later, standing among them. The hunger gnaws deep. Your skin is cold. Your voice is gone. You are one of them now. <h1>UNDEAD</h1> [[Restart->starting]]You leave the barn, walking down your lane. At the end, you spot a familiar figure by the hedgerow — Elliot, Jane’s lad. He stands there awkwardly, rucksack sagging off one shoulder, pale face staring down the empty road. “Alright, El?” you call. He jumps at the sound, then turns. “Oh… hi,” he says flatly. “Bus still hasn’t come. Been waiting ages.” You trade quick words. The power’s out. Phones are dead. The roads are empty. Elliot’s relief at seeing someone he knows is obvious, though his eyes are restless, scanning the mist. Before you can say more, a sound cuts through the stillness. Footsteps. Slow. Wrong. An old woman rounds the bend — cardigan soaked, one shoe missing, eyes glazed red. She keeps coming, fixed on you both. " alt="My Image" style="width: 200px;"> You drive the empty roads past RNAS Culdrose and through Helston. Shopfronts shuttered. Pavements bare. Bins overturned and rolling in the breeze. You leave Helston, taking the winding country lanes towards the A30. Near Wendron, you round a bend and stop the road is blocked by a fresh-looking pile-up wedged in the narrow lane. One car is upside down, roof flattened against tarmac. Another sits sideways, door hanging open. You kill the engine and step out. It looks bad. No police. No ambulance. But the blood doesn’t look fresh, and the rainbow sheen of oil trails has settled into dull patches. Movement. From the car on its roof. You kneel and crawl to the shattered window. Inside, a young woman hangs pinned in her belt, a deep gash across her neck. She moans, a wet, dragging sound. “You okay?” you ask, reaching in. Her head snaps towards you. Eyes blood red. Her hand shoots out. Nails rake your wrist. You jerk back, scramble to your feet and your world tilts. A hot knife of pain drives into your gut. Your legs fold. Blackness closes in. You wake moments later, standing among them. The hunger gnaws deep. Your skin is cold. Your voice is gone. " alt="My Image" style="width: 200px;"> You sit there, telling yourself it’s fine you’ve still got battery power on the laptop. With a grunt, you switch the UPS over and manage to squeeze out a bit more juice. A little admin work. A quick game. Anything to distract yourself. But the power never comes back. You sigh, wishing you’d saved the UPS for the coffee machine instead. That’s when a sound filters in through the barn walls a low, drawn-out moaning. Curious, you step outside. Near the edge of the lane, a group staggers through the mist. Clothes torn, faces smeared with blood. One of them looks horribly familiar, Jane’s lad. Elliot. “You lot alright?” you call, moving closer. No answer. Just vacant eyes and twitching hands. You take another step. That’s when they surge forward. Too fast. Too many. Hands claw. Teeth sink. Pain flares white-hot. You scream, but it dies in your throat. Darkness takes you. You wake again moments later, standing among them. The hunger gnaws deep. Your skin is cold. Your voice is gone. You are one of them now. <h1>UNDEAD</h1> [[Restart->starting]]You swing the car around at the roundabout and head back. As you pull up just past the bus stop, you spot him. Elliot. Jane’s lad. Standing by the hedge, rucksack dangling, pale face scanning the road. You wind down the window. “Alright, El?” He startles, then gives a thin smile. “Bus still hasn’t come. Been waiting ages.” You kill the engine and step out, joining him at the roadside. You trade quick words power’s out, phones are dead, roads silent. Elliot’s relief at seeing you is clear, though he looks shaken. Before you can say more, a sound cuts through the stillness. Footsteps. Slow. Wrong. An old woman rounds the bend — cardigan soaked, one shoe missing, eyes glazed red. She keeps coming, fixed on you both. [[Stand your ground and try to talk to her->PatTalk]] [[Back away towards the barn->PatRetreat]] You plant your feet and raise your voice. “Pat? It’s Callum. Stop there, love. You’re scaring the boy.” She doesn’t stop. Her head tilts, jaw slack, eyes blood-red and empty. Then she lunges — far too fast for her age. You try to push her back, but her hands claw at your jacket, teeth snapping. Hot pain explodes in your arm as she bites down hard. “Jesus!” you yell, shoving against her. Blood soaks through your sleeve. Elliot rushes forward to help, panic in his eyes. “Get off him!” he shouts, grabbing at her shoulders. Pat twists, jaws snapping again — and this time she latches onto Elliot. He screams as blood spatters the lane. The two of you collapse together, pain flooding your bodies. Your breaths grow shallow. The world dims. Then you wake. Standing. Hungry. Cold. Silent. Elliot is beside you, eyes the same shade of red. Together, you stumble forward. <h1>UNDEAD</h1> [[Restart->starting]]You and Elliot edge back, step by shaky step, towards the barn. She doesn’t slow. She doesn’t speak. She just keeps coming. At the threshold you yank the door open, slip inside, and slam the bolt. Thud. Thud. A dragging hand scrapes across the wood. “We need something to fight with,” Elliot whispers. " alt="My Image" style="width: 200px;"> You slow, then crank the wheel into a sharp three-point turn, tyres biting into gravel as you swing the car around towards Gweek. Just outside the village, you round a bend and slam the brakes. The road is sealed off by a pile-up, jammed tight in the narrow lane. One car lies upside down, its roof crushed flat against the tarmac. Another is skewed across the road Then movement from the car on its roof. You crouch low, peering through the shattered window. Inside, a young woman dangles from her seatbelt, throat split by a deep gash. Her breath rattles out in a wet, dragging moan. “Hey—are you alright?” you whisper, reaching in. Her head snaps towards you. Eyes—blood red. Her hand lashes out, nails raking deep across your wrist. You wrench back, stumbling to your feet but pain lances your stomach like a hot blade. Your legs buckle. The world spins. Darkness swallows. When you open your eyes, you’re standing. But not breathing. Not alive. The hunger burns through you. Your skin is ice. Your voice is gone. Elliot’s voice cuts through the haze as he runs towards you. You turn. Snarl. He barely has time to cry out before your teeth tear into him. Moments later, the two of you stand side by side in the stillness of the lane. <h1>UNDEAD</h1> [[Restart->starting]]You reach the hospital with Elliot, tyres screeching as the Porsche dies to silence outside. You push inside. The air is stale, thick with dust and the copper tang of blood. “Mum! Mum!” Elliot’s voice cracks as it echoes down the corridor. “MUM!” From somewhere deep in the building comes a faint whimper. Hope flashes across Elliot’s face. But behind you moaning. Scratching. The shuffle of feet. You spin. Shapes move in the dim light. Dozens of Zombies. They surge forward, faster than you can react. Hands claw. Teeth tear. You fight, but it’s hopeless. They drag you down. Their weight crushes the breath from your lungs. Beside you, Elliot screams as they pile onto him too. From the far room, his mother emerges eyes wide, tears streaking her face. She sees you both go under, sees her son’s cries cut off in a wet, choking gurgle. “No… no, please…” she whispers, sinking to her knees. The sobs wrack her chest, but there’s no mercy here. The dead turn on her. Her scream rises, breaks then ends. " alt="My Image" style="width: 200px;"> You ease off the throttle, the Porsche snarling as you wrench the wheel around. Gravel spits out from under the tyres as you skid in a wide arc and head back towards the back gate. The soldiers are still there shouting, firing, the line buckling under the weight of the dead. The scene is chaos. What do you do? [[Ram the horde with your car->ram]] [[Lean on the horn to draw them away->horn]] You slam your foot down. The Porsche leaps forward with a roar, tyres shrieking as you hurl it straight into the mass. Impact. Bodies crunch beneath the bumper, shattering against the bonnet, flung up and over the roof. The windscreen explodes in a spray of gore. The soldiers stare wide-eyed as you carve through the horde, scattering the dead like broken mannequins. But then the car jolts violently, snagging on a twisted limb wedged beneath the chassis. The engine screams. The acrid stench of burning rubber fills the air. The horde is broken, for now… but not beaten. You’ve only bought seconds. Gunfire rattles from the soldiers. Wild. Panicked. One stray burst punches through the car Elliot gasps, clutching his chest, blood soaking his hoodie. You lean over to reach him and a round smashes through your skull. Blackness. <h1>DEAD</h1> [[Restart->starting]]You slam your palm onto the horn. A long, blaring note shatters the moaning. The horde reacts instantly. Heads whip around. Dozens peel away from the soldiers and lurch towards you, clawing the air, shrieking with hunger. It works, the soldiers have breathing space, firing into them. Indie authors live and breathe by your feedback, and it makes all the difference. [[Restart->starting]]“Bugger this,” Tomo muttered. He hauled himself back onto the tractor seat. The old engine coughed, then rattled into life, drowning the morning silence. The figures turned at the sound, drifting towards the noise—slow, but steady. Tomo dropped the clutch and carried on, tilling a clean length of soil before swinging the rig back down the row. When he glanced up, he saw them clustered at the gate, pressing against the bars but not crossing. Just stuck there. Watching. His jaw tightened. [[Keep your head down and carry on ignoring them->Ignore2]] [[Enough’s enough. March over and have it out with them->speak]] Tomo muttered, “Bugger this. Let the bloody police deal with the smack 'eads.” He hauled himself back into the tractor, The old engine coughed, rattled, then roared as he shoved it into gear. The figures in the field shambled after the noise, but Tomo kept his eyes ahead and drove on. He rattled through the gate, swung the tractor onto the lane and slammed the brakes. A woman staggered right into his path. Wild hair plastered to her face, bare feet, she seemed to waving something and yelling “Jesus wept,” Tomo breathed, heart hammering. He’d nearly flattened her. And she looked madder than a box of frogs. [[Lean out and talk at her->tomo_shout]] [[Stay in the cab and gun the engine->tomo_driveon]] Tomo slammed the tractor into neutral and climbed down, muttering under his breath. “Right then. Let’s see what they're bleedy problem is.” He strode across the furrows, boots heavy in the tilled soil. The figures were still pressed up against the gate, twitching and swaying like drunks at closing time. “Oi! This is private land!” he barked, coming closer. That’s when one shot a hand out—fingers curled like claws. It raked across his face, hot lines of pain burning his cheek. Tomo staggered back, shocked more than hurt. His heel caught in the loose earth. He stumbled, went down hard into the soft soil. For a heartbeat he thought he could scramble up— but then the pain hit. A white-hot stab in his gut that stole the strength from his limbs. His breath caught. The world spun. His hands went slick with blood. Above him, the figures loomed, snarling and clawing. He tried to shout, but only a groan escaped as the strength bled out of him. Darkness closed in. When his eyes opened again, the field was the same. The gate was the same. But everything looked different. Red. Hungry. Endless. <h1>UNDEAD</h1> [[Restart->starting]] The tractor rattled on, Tomo keeping his eyes down on the soil. Best to ignore the daft buggers at the gate. Not his problem. But when he turned back down the row, his stomach dropped. More of them now. Fifteen, maybe more. They’d forced a gap in the hedge and were spilling into the field, stumbling through the fresh furrows towards the sound of the engine. Tomo swore under his breath. “What the bleedy hell do they think they’re doing?” He pulled the tractor over, killed the throttle, and climbed down. Boots thudded into the dirt as he marched across the tilled earth, ash stick in hand. His mood wasn’t fear anymore. It was anger. This was his land. His field. But as he got closer, the anger wavered. Their clothes were soaked in dark stains. Their faces were grey, their eyes glassy red. Blood glistened down their chins. He froze. And in that single moment of hesitation, they lunged. The first clamped onto his arm, teeth punching through the jacket. Another bit into his shoulder, then more piled on—pulling him down into the dirt, teeth tearing, hot pain flaring across every limb. Tomo roared, tried to shove them off, but there were too many. His cries turned to choked gasps as the weight pressed him flat, the world dimming in flashes of pain. Then silence. When he opened his eyes again, the sky was still above him—grey, heavy with mist. But the world looked different. Sharper. Hungrier. His vision burned red. His breath was gone. And the hunger gnawed deep. <h1>UNDEAD</h1> [[Restart->starting]] Tomo slammed the tractor into neutral and climbed down, muttering under his breath. “Right then. Let’s see what they're bleedy problem is.” He strode across the furrows, boots heavy in the tilled soil. The figures were still pressed up against the gate, twitching and swaying like drunks at closing time. “Oi! This is private land!” he barked, coming closer. That’s when one shot a hand out—fingers curled like claws. It raked across his face, hot lines of pain burning his cheek. Tomo staggered back, shocked more than hurt. His heel caught in the loose earth. He stumbled, went down hard into the soft soil. For a heartbeat he thought he could scramble up— but then the pain hit. A white-hot stab in his gut that stole the strength from his limbs. His breath caught. The world spun. His hands went slick with blood. Above him, the figures loomed, snarling and clawing. He tried to shout, but only a groan escaped as the strength bled out of him. Darkness closed in. When his eyes opened again, the field was the same. The gate was the same. But everything looked different. Red. Hungry. Endless. <h1>UNDEAD</h1> [[Restart->starting]] Tomo leaned out of the cab window, one hand gripping the door. “You alright, maid? Wass-on with ’ee?” he called, voice raised over the engine. The woman stopped in the lane, barefoot, hoodie soaked, hair plastered to her face. She looked wild-eyed and half gone like she’d run a mile through hell. Her hands trembled as she waved at him. “Stop! Please, you have to stop!” Tomo’s frown softened. Up close she didn’t look like the shamblers in his field. She was frantic, yes, but sharp too words, not just moans. He braked hard, the tractor grumbling to a halt, and pushed the door open. She stumbled to the side of the cab, clutching at the wheel arch. “I—I didn’t mean to… He came at me, there was blood, his eyes… oh God, I think he’s dead…” Her words tumbled out in a rush, voice breaking. “Name’s Tomo,” he said gruffly. “Reckon somethin’s not right out here.” She swallowed hard. “Jessica,” she managed. “And… yeah. Something’s very wrong.” [[Continue->tomo_and_jessica]]Tomo "not another freak" he faced the front and accelirated she moved out the way and te trator bardged past... she shouted at him as it past... The house stood quiet, nothing out of place. Inside, he kicked his boots off at the back door and muttered, “Bugger this morning…” Straight to the kitchen. He flicked the kettle on nothing. Power was out. “Bleedy ell.” With a grunt, he knelt by the Rayburn, stacked kindling, and struck a match. Soon the stove glowed with steady heat. He set the old blackened kettle on top, steam curling in the warm kitchen air. Minutes later he was sat at the table, hands wrapped round a chipped mug, the rich smell of tea cutting through the damp. For the first time that day, he breathed easy. A couple of hours passed before the itch got him. He needed to check the stock. Needed to look over the fields. Pulling his boots back on, Tomo stepped out into the yard. The late light hung low, shadows stretching. That’s when he saw them. Dozens now, staggering through the lower meadow, pouring through gaps in the hedgerows, drifting closer with every step. Tomo spat on the ground. “For fuck’s sake. What you after now, eh?” He stomped down towards them, ash stick in hand, ready to give a piece of his mind. But when he got close enough to see their faces, the bravado faltered. Pale skin. Blood smeared across their clothes. Eyes glowing red in the half-light. “Jesus Christ…” One lurched forward, faster than the rest, and sank its teeth into his arm before he could swing. He howled, staggered back, but more hands grabbed him, dragging him down into the mud. The pain was blinding, teeth tearing into him again and again. His roar turned ragged, then thin, then nothing. When Tomo opened his eyes again, the yard was still. The sky above darkening. But all he felt was hunger. <h1>UNDEAD</h1> [[Restart->starting]]Tomo and Jessica made it to his brother’s farm. With a guttural snarl they broke into a lurching sprint—straight at him. Pain flared—then fire in his gut. He fell. Darkness. When he eyes opened, he was standing. But not alive. Not human. " alt="My Image" style="width: 200px;"> Tomo agrees and takes her back to the cottage near the sea. tomo says he is going to his Tomo finally nodded. “Alright, Jess. If that’s what you want.” He dropped her at the cottage by the sea. “I’m heading to my brother’s,” he said, reluctant. She forced a smile. “I’ll be okay.” Exhausted, she locked the doors, packed a small bag, and collapsed into bed. Hours later she woke, convinced it had all been a nightmare. She loaded her car and drove north. Just outside the village, she rounded a bend—slammed the brakes. The road was blocked, cars wrecked and tangled. One lay upside down, roof crushed. From inside, faint movement. Jessica crept closer. A young woman hung from her seatbelt, throat torn, breath rattling. “Hey… you alright?” The girl’s head snapped. Eyes red. A clawing hand slashed Jessica’s wrist. Pain flared—then fire in her gut. She fell. Darkness. When her eyes opened, she was standing. But not alive. Not human. The hunger consumed her. <h1>UNDEAD</h1> [[Restart->starting]] The tractor rumbled back into gear, Jessica gripping the side as Tomo drove them towards Helston. The fields gave way to houses, then the outskirts of town. Up ahead, near the hospital, a group of people stood scattered across the road. Something about them was off. Their clothes were torn, their movements jerky, wrong. One turned its head too far, too slow, fixing on the sound of the engine. Jessica’s voice was barely a whisper. “Tomo… what are they?” * [[Tomo slows the tractor to take a closer look.->HospitalClose]] * [[He swerves wide to avoid them and keeps driving.->HospitalBypass]] Elliot groaned and swung his legs out of bed. The room felt colder than he’d hoped, the morning creeping in. Now what? [[Head to the kitchen for a drink|ElliotKitchen]] [[Slump in front of the TV|ElliotTV]] Elliot drifted back into sleep. When he finally stirred again it was nearly midday, hunger and a full bladder dragging him upright. Sunlight blared through the curtains, too bright, too sharp. He shuffled to the window and blinked out. A handful of people wandered up the street, their movements uneven, staggering. They looked drunk. Elliot frowned, but thought little of it. Downstairs, the house was silent. The power was out, and his phone was dead. With nothing else to do, he raided the fridge and slapped together a cheese sandwich. That’s when the banging started heavy, urgent, rattling the front door. Curiosity beat caution. He opened it. An old woman lunged at him, eyes glazed, hands clawing. The pain was blinding, teeth tearing into him again and again. His roar turned ragged, then thin, then nothing. When Tomo opened his eyes again, the yard was still. The sky above darkening. But all he felt was hunger. <h1>UNDEAD</h1> [[Restart->starting]]He shuffled into the kitchen, the floor cool beneath his feet. The tap squeaked as he filled a glass. That’s when he noticed the answer machine flashing red, the little light blinking in the half-dark. He pressed play. His mum’s voice crackled through, tired but steady she was still at work, saying she’d be late again and not to wait up. The message ended, leaving the room a little too quiet. Mum must have gone out early this morning,* he thought. Strange… he hadn’t heard her leave. Elliot rubbed his face and muttered, *“Sod it, may as well get the bus.”* He sprayed on a cloud of Lynx, shoved in his earbuds, and stepped out of the house. Eyes glued to his phone, music blaring, he almost walked straight into an old lady in blood-soaked clothes. She turned on him fast and bit down before he could even react.
